INSERT INTO marketing_content_tracker (client_id, platform, date, post_type, script, status, link, time, caption, views, likes, comments, shares, saves, follows, avg_watch_time_pct, boosted, engagement_rate_pct, save_rate_pct, content_score, youtube_views, youtube_watch_time, youtube_avg_view_duration, youtube_ctr, source) VALUES (2, 'instagram', '2026-06-17', 'Reel', 'Reel 1: Iron




**AUDIENCE:** Indian women trying to conceive or currently pregnant, ages 24–38, following a gynecologist for honest, easy-to-understand advice.


**RESEARCH INSIGHT USED:** Approximately half of all pregnant women in India are anaemic — over 7.5 million women. [Wiley Online Library](https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/mcn.13684) And haemoglobin is the last place iron drops — ferritin goes first, meaning a woman can be iron deficient for months before any report shows it. [Core Med Science](https://coremedscience.com/blogs/wellness/iron-deficiency-without-anemia-why-pregnant-women-should-get-screenings-for-iron-deficiency)




**[0:00–0:03] HOOK (🔴 OPEN LOOP 1)**

Strategy: Contrarian Comment YES if you want me to cover more supplements like this.


*"I’m tired all the time,my hair is falling, and I just feel off. My haemoglobin is normal — but.. I don’t know.. I hear this from my patients every single day."*


---


**[0:03–0:10] LOOP OPENER (🔴 OPEN LOOP 2 | 🔴 HOLD LOOP 1)**

Strategy: Awareness Trigger


*"Here''s something most people don''t know. Haemoglobin is actually the last thing to drop when your iron is low. By the time it shows on your report — your body''s iron stores have been empty for months already. There''s another test called ferritin. That''s the one that catches it early. And most routine checkups don''t even include it."*


---


**[0:10–0:25] MIDDLE (🟢 CLOSE LOOP 1 | 🔴 OPEN LOOP 3)**

Strategy: Credibility Establish + Consequence War


*"In India, about half of all pregnant women are anaemic. That''s not a small number. And for most of us — because we eat vegetarian — it''s even harder, because plant-based iron is much more difficult for the body to absorb. During pregnancy, your iron requirement almost doubles. And your baby takes what it needs first — for the brain, for the blood, for everything. Whatever is left, that''s what you have. So when iron is low, it''s not just tiredness. It can mean early delivery. Low birth weight. And complications at the time of delivery."*


---


**[0:25–0:38] RESOLUTION (🟢 CLOSE LOOP 2 & 3)**

Strategy: Relatability Mirror


*"The good news — your daily food already helps. Dal, palak, rajma, chana — keep eating these. But add a little lemon or amla with your meals. Vitamin C helps your body actually absorb the iron. And one thing I really want you to remember — don''t have chai or coffee right after eating. That alone blocks a lot of iron absorption. If your doctor has given you an iron supplement, take it on an empty stomach. And please ask for a ferritin test — not just haemoglobin."*


---


**[0:38–0:43] FINAL CLOSE (🟢 ALL CLOSED)**

Strategy: Mirror of Hook


*"A normal haemoglobin report doesn''t always mean your iron is fine. Ask for the ferritin test at your next visit."*


---


**[0:43–0:45] CTA**


*"Comment YES if you want me to break down more supplements like this."*


---


**VISUAL NOTES:**

— Doctor smiling slightly, relaxed — approachable, not serious

— Text overlay: "Half of pregnant women in India" — clean, no drama

— Show dal, palak, rajma, lemon squeeze — familiar, homey visuals

— Chai cup next to food plate for that one line — instant recognition

— Final line: calm, direct, no music', 'Posted', 'https://www.instagram.com/reel/DZrsoAVzD41/?igsh=MXI2dW9tamYyc2t3aw==', '15:30', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'No', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'migration');
